\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 STATEMENTS OF INTEREST
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The CENTER FOR CONSTITUTIONAL RIGHTS (CCR) was created in 1966 by lawyers who were active in the civil rights movement and the struggle of women and ethnic minorities in the United States for true equality.  CCR attorneys have been involved in cases concerning voting rights, community control of schools, fair housing, employment discrimination, jury composition, and international human rights.  Through litigation and public education CCR has worked to make meaningful the constitutional statutory, and international rights of women, Blacks, Puerto Ricans, Native Americans, Asians, and Chicanos.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The Center for Constitutional Rights joins with amici to urge the Court to uphold this ordinance, which represents the attempts of local governments nationwide to combat the escalating violence against People of Color, women, and other historically oppressed groups.  Failing to uphold this statute,  \b \i0 \ul0 [*45]\b0 \i0 \ul0   which threatens no constitutionally protected expression, will send the dangerous message that this society, at its highest levels, will continue to tolerate vicious brutality directed against people because of their race, ethnicity, gender, sexual orientation and religion.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The CENTER FOR DEMOCRATIC RENEWAL (CDR) is a national, non-profit, tax-exempt clearinghouse for information on constructive, non-violent responses to hate group activity and bigoted violence.  Founded in 1979 as the National Anti-Klan Network, today the CDR conducts programs of research, leadership training, community organizing, public education and litigation.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 With offices in Atlanta, Georgia, Kansas City, Missouri, and Seattle, Washington, the CDR also aids the victims of bigoted violence through telephone counseling and emergency assistance.  The CDR serves a diverse constituency of more than 10,000 members and supporters throughout the United States.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The CDR believes that municipal, state and federal legislation addressing the problem of hate crimes can both deter acts of bigoted violence and send a strong signal that such acts are not sanctioned by the community.  The CDR wishes to join as an amicus \b \i0 \ul0 [*46]\b0 \i0 \ul0   curiae in this case in order to lend the perspective of a national, multi-racial, interfaith organization dedicated to preserving and enhancing the rights of all persons victimized by bigotry and intolerance.  The CDR is of the belief that the constitutionality of the St. Paul, Minnesota, ordinance in question should be upheld.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The GREATER BOSTON CIVIL RIGHTS COALITION (GBCRC) was founded in 1979 to address increases in racial, religious and ethnic violence within the Greater Boston area.  The coalition was founded during the height of the busing and desegregation controversy that racked the city of Boston.  Today, the GBCRC is a coalition of over 100 private and public civil rights, law enforcement, religious, community and grass roots organizations who meet together regularly to discuss issues of discrimination based on race, religion and ethnic origin.  Among the priorities of the BGCRC, four have remained paramount over the past decade of the GBCRC's work:
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 * Advancing the progress of civil rights by fostering harmonious racial, religious and ethnic relations.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 * Improving communication among participating organizations.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 * Training of law enforcement personnel in dealing \b \i0 \ul0 [*47]\b0 \i0 \ul0   with hate crime and violations of civil rights.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 * Focusing on shaping public and private policy as it relates to discrimination in the political, economic and social realms.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 * Advocating for the effective use of civil rights laws to deter hate crimes.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The GBCRC took the most prominent role of any organization in gaining the enactment of the Massachusetts Hate Crime Reporting Act, signed into law in December of 1990.  That Act mandates the collection of hate crime data for the first time in the history of the Commonwealth; in direct response to the work of the Coalition, Governor William Weld recently appointed a Hate Crime Reporting Implementation Task Force, on which the GBCRC has several seats.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The Coalition members support legislation to recognize the severity of hate crime and its resounding impact on effected communities.  The Coalition strongly believes that hate crime perpetrators should be punished for their acts, and that such punishment sends a message to both the victimized community and its victimizers: that acts of terror and hate based on the race, religion or ethnic background of an individual or a community will be punished.  We firmly support the right of communities \b \i0 \ul0 [*48]\b0 \i0 \ul0   to enact legislation which consistent with first amendment protection prohibits unlawful hate crime.  We firmly support the application of the St. Paul ordinance to combat the hate crime in the instant case.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The INTERNATIONAL UNION, UNITED AUTOMOBILE, AEROSPACE AND AGRICULTURAL IMPLEMENT WORKERS OF AMERICA (UAW), is a labor organization with approximately one million members headquartered in Detroit, Michigan.  The UAW is an industrial union representing private and public employees throughout the United States.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Since its inception in the 1930s, the UAW has been an instrumental part of the Civil Rights movement in the United States.  In the 1940s, the UAW established a Fair Practices Committee to monitor and improve the treatment of workers in the plants and to strive for broader racial justice in society.  In the 1950s and 1960s, the UAW worked with its allies for desegregation, voting rights, equal employment opportunity, and fair housing.  In the 1970s, the union won contractual non-discrimination protection in its collective bargaining agreements and the establishment of Civil Rights Committees in its local unions.  In both the 1970s and 1980s, the UAW supported the adoption \b \i0 \ul0 [*49]\b0 \i0 \ul0   of improved federal, state, and local legislation protecting minorities, women, and others subjected to the discrimination and bigotry still all too prevalent in our society.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Despite the progress made in the last sixty years toward racial justice in this county, there remains a strong undercurrent of virulent racism and sexism which too often manifests itself in hate crimes, violence, threats, and intimidation.  In response, many states and localities have enacted legislation intended to protect citizens from the tangible harm which results from being subjected to these actions.  In order to support these state and local initiatives, the UAW joins in this amicus brief.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The NATIONAL COALITION FOR BLACK LESBIANS AND GAYS (NCBLG) is the oldest Black organization in the country working to advocate and promote the empowerment and enhancement of the lesbian and gay community.  Formally a chapter organization with branches in Baltimore, Chicago, Detroit, New York and Oakland/San Francisco, the national office is located in Washington D.C.  We have over 500 members nationally and our numbers are on the increase.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 NCBLG is presently working and addressing legislative policy and educational \b \i0 \ul0 [*50]\b0 \i0 \ul0   concerns that constantly confront the diverse communities of the country.  NCBLG finds that there is a need in the community for workshops, seminars, and lectures to provide training on these issues, as well as other initiatives such as our Project Dialogue, HIV/AIDS information and the Leadership Development series.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Since NCBLG began in 1979, it has been dedicated to equal rights and civil liberties for the entire community regardless of race, gender, or sexual orientation.  In spite of the strides that have been accomplished in the last 50 years, injustice continues to be prevalent.  This is evident by the increase of hate crimes throughout the country.  NCBLG wishes to join other progressive organizations which work to protect all citizens from the physical and psychological harm which may be a by-product of these bias-related crimes.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The NATIONAL CONFERENCE OF BLACK LAWYERS (NCBL) is a non-profit organization founded in 1968, and comprised of over 2500 lawyers, law students, legal workers and other individuals working for social justice.  NCBL and its members engage in affirmative litigation and activities to challenge and correct acts of injustice based on race, sex, religion \b \i0 \ul0 [*51]\b0 \i0 \ul0   and other irrational biases.  Cross burning is without question such an act.  We agree with the Minnesota Supreme Court's characterization of cross burning as a symbol of violence and hatred based on notions of racial supremacy.  Because cross burning represents the kind of abominable "speech" that we are working to eliminate, NCBL joins the other amici in urging this Court to uphold the Minnesota statute as constitutional.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The NATIONAL COUNCIL OF LA RAZA (NCLR), the largest constituency-based national Hispanic organization, exists to improve life opportunities for the more than 22 million Americans of Hispanic descent.  NCLR acts as an umbrella organization for its 139 affiliated Hispanic community-based organizations, which together serve 35 states, the District of Columbia, and Puerto Rico and reach more than one million Hispanics annually.  NCLR has four missions: applied research, policy analysis and advocacy on behalf of the entire Hispanic community; capacity-building assistance to support and strengthen Hispanic community-based organizations; public information activities designed to provide accurate information and positive images of Hispanics; and special innovative, catalytic,  \b \i0 \ul0 [*52]\b0 \i0 \ul0   and international projects.  In addition to its Washington, D.C. national headquarters, NCLR maintains field offices in Los Angeles, California; Phoenix, Arizona; McAllen, Texas; and Chicago, Illinois.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 NCLR has long recognized that Hispanics are frequently the victims of hate crimes and the targets of violent threats and intimidating behavior (i.e., "fighting words") because of prejudice toward national origin characteristics such as physical appearance, language or speech accent, and cultural characteristics.  NCLR is, therefore, particularly interested in the St. Paul crossburning statute case, R.A.V. v. City of St. Paul, because of its important implications for the maintenance of constitutional protection from such dangerous behavior.  NCLR would like to join this amicus brief to show its support for the position that the prohibition of intimidating and harassing conduct in the subject case is constitutionally permissible.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The NATIONAL INSTITUTE AGAINST PREJUDICE AND VIOLENCE (NIAPV) is the only national center dedicated exclusively to the study of and response to violence motivated by prejudice - "ethnoviolence".  Founded in 1984, NIAPV is a not-for-profit tax-exempt organization \b \i0 \ul0 [*53]\b0 \i0 \ul0   under Section 501(c)(3) of the Internal Revenue Code.  NIAPV conducts research on the causes of ethnoviolence and its effect on victims and communities; serves as a clearinghouse of information; and provides education and consultation including human relations training, legal and policy analysis, and assistance to agencies and organizations.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 NIAPV has conducted pioneering research on the prevalence and impact of ethnoviolent victimization on college campuses, in the workplace, and in the larger community.  In its National Victimization Survey, the first national study of its kind, NIAPV established that acts of violence motivated by prejudice have greater traumatic impact on victims than do other forms of victimization.  In addition, NIAPV is publisher of the most comprehensive legal manual available on criminal and civil remedies for violence motivated by prejudice.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Intergroup prejudice and violence tear at the very fabric of our society.  NIAPV believes that states have a compelling interest in protecting both individual victims and the larger community through legal remedies which recognize the unique harm inflicted by acts of bigoted violence.  NIAPV further believes that in \b \i0 \ul0 [*54]\b0 \i0 \ul0   tailoring criminal sanctions and civil remedies to address this unique harm, states do not thereby infringe on our precious First Amendment freedoms as they have been defined in decisions of the United States Supreme Court.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The NATIONAL LAWYERS GUILD (Guild) is a national organization representing over 10,000 lawyers, legal workers, law students and jailhouse lawyers in over 200 chapters throughout the United States.  Since its founding in 1937, the Guild has provided legal support to virtually every struggle in this country for economic, social and political justice.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The rise of hate and bias related acts in the form of speech and conduct in the past several years presents this society with the challenge to reconcile civil liberties principles of equal protection and free expression.  The Guild opposes bias, bigotry, and discrimination on the basis of race, gender, sexual orientation and religion.  When acts of hate, viewed in their historical context of perpetuating racial supremacy, infringe upon the ability of people of color and others to enjoy equality free of racial discrimination, the actor ought to be punished by the law.  Examples of such acts include cross burnings,  \b \i0 \ul0 [*55]\b0 \i0 \ul0   the placement of swastikas and the intimidating wearing of the Ku Klux Klan hood.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The National Lawyers Guild joins with the other amici curiae in this important case of public concern to present its views on the legal effort to combat White supremacy.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The NATIONAL ORGANIZATION OF BLACK LAW ENFORCEMENT EXECUTIVES (NOBLE) is a non-profit organization of police chiefs, agency heads, command-level law enforcement officials and criminal justice educators whose membership is numbered at approximately 2400.  NOBLE's goals are to develop, implement and manage innovative ideas, concepts and programs aimed at reducing violence, crime, and the elimination of racism in the criminal justice arena.  NOBLE was founded in September, 1976, during a three day symposium co-sponsored by the Police Foundation and the Law Enforcement Assistance Administration (LEAA).
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Consistent with its motto, "Justice by Action," NOBLE aggressively pursues its goals by conducting substantive research, speaking out on the issues and performing a variety of outreach activities.  NOBLE's success in this arena is reflected by its growth and the major role it has played, and continues to play, in shaping policy in areas \b \i0 \ul0 [*56]\b0 \i0 \ul0   of vital importance to minorities and the law enforcement community.  NOBLE has effectively used the judicial process and direct correspondence to express opinions and concerns.  NOBLE has endorsed strategies that provide a holistic approach to crime and violence and proactive police-community involvement.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 What has come to be known as hate violence, racial and religious violence and harassment was first researched by NOBLE in 1983.  NOBLE received funding from the National Institute of Justice (NIJ) to do research on the problem and to develop model policies and procedures for law enforcement agencies.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 As a result, NOBLE published a law enforcement handbook that outlines a model response to racial and religious violence which is used broadly by the law enforcement community and social service practitioners.  NOBLE provided education and advocacy that resulted in the passage of federal legislation requiring the collection of data on the occurrence of hate violence incidents.  With a grant from the Ford Foundation, NOBLE has drafted a training program and produced a videotape for law enforcement workers on racial violence entitled Hate Crime: a Police Perspective aimed at training \b \i0 \ul0 [*57]\b0 \i0 \ul0   police officers in effective procedures for handling hate crimes.  In addition, NOBLE has developed a training curriculum to deal with cultural clashes on college campuses.  The curriculum is designed to sensitize college administrators, students and law enforcement personnel to the issue of racism.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Consequently, we are particularly interested in supporting the constitutionality of the city of St. Paul's ordinance that is the subject of this amicus brief, and we wish to join in this amicus brief.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The UNITED CHURCH OF CHRIST COMMISSION FOR RACIAL JUSTICE (CRJ) is the national civil rights agency of the 1.6 million-member United Church of Christ.  The Commission has long been actively in-volved in the struggles for racial justice and social equality of African Americans and other minority communities in the United States.  Established in 1963 by the General Synod of the United Church of Christ in response to the assassination of Medgar Evers, the Birmingham church bombings, and the heightened racial tension then gripping the nation, CRJ has been at the forefront of the civil rights movement as a church-based agency of a major U.S. Protestant denomination.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 CRJ programs have focused \b \i0 \ul0 [*58]\b0 \i0 \ul0   on a diverse range of issues, including: African American family life, capital punishment and penal reform, voter registration, racially motivated violence, child abuse, displaced homemakers, battered wives, teenage pregnancy, welfare hotels and homelessness, persons with disabilities, computer literacy, environmental racism, the empowerment of African American, Hispanic American, Asian Pacific American and Native American communities, and increasing the percentage of minority students in colleges through its scholarship program.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 For 29 years the Commission for Racial Justice has fought racial bigotry in all of its expressions.  We deplore acts of racist violence and see this case as a major opportunity for the court to affirm local governments in their efforts to thwart bias-related violence.  Incidents of racist violence are occurring daily across this country.  Equal rights and human rights must be extended to all, and not diminished by racist, violent acts of others.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The YOUNG WOMENT'S CHRISTIAN ASSOCIATION OF THE U.S.A. (YWCA) is a national membership organization serving 2 million women and their families dedicated to the empowerment of women and the elimination of racism.  \b \i0 \ul0 [*59]\b0 \i0 \ul0   Since 1858, the YWCA of the U.S.A. has addressed the critical connection between providing services for women, girls, and their families and acting to correct societal conditions that create the need for those services.  Our members represent varied economic, social, racial, ethnic, and religious groups committed to the struggle for justice and equity and peace.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The YWCA's One Imperative, "To thrust our collective power toward the elimination of racism wherever it exists and by any means necessary," stems from our commitment to this struggle.  In both our programmatic and our advocacy work we are particularly concerned with the growing numbers of racially motivated acts of violence and targeted expressions of hatred.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 We believe that properly drafted statutes may be a significant deterrent to expressions of bias engendered hatred and bigoted violence.  When one individual of an historically oppressed group becomes victim to a crime based on her or his membership in that group, all members of the group experience fear and intimidation.  The YWCA of the U.S.A. wishes to join as amicus curiae in this case to contribute our unique perspective of a multi-ethnic, interfaith women's membership \b \i0 \ul0 [*60]\b0 \i0 \ul0   movement with the imperative to eliminate racism.  We are of the opinion that the constitutionality of the St. Paul, Minnesota, ordinance in question should be upheld.
